{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0dfa0b15-8997-4c0d-8bf4-bd522c74d07c","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace root with a `stdio` transport that runs `dotnet run`:\n\n```jsonc\n// .vscode/mcp.json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"],\n      \"env\": {\n        // add any environment variables your server needs\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — launches via `dotnet run`. Adjust the `--project` path if your workspace root differs.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, point `command` directly at the executable.\n- Your server must use **stdio** transport (not HTTP/SSE) for agent mode with this config.\n\nAfter saving, restart VS Code or run **\"MCP: List Servers\"** from the command palette to verify it connects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0f8593e4-0979-4ba4-bcf1-57a3deca20ba","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but the user says they built it. Regardless, I can still provide guidance on how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server with VS Code agent mode.\n\nFor VS Code agent mode, you configure MCP servers in `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace. For a C# project using stdio transport, the configuration would use `dotnet run` to launch the server.","outputTokens":390,"requestId":"201D:3DEB8E:1C13C0F:1F1BA75:6A0521F8"},"id":"1c832d78-a7cb-45f0-bf84-3b3e957ce05e","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:14:42.623Z","parentId":"02735602-2da3-457d-970a-4b0f4d1bd77c"}
